WESTERN CIVILIZATION EQUIVALENT (OPERATIONAL SYSTEM)
Aligned to the same 4-pillar architecture (释 构 度 行)

------------------------------------------------------------
【CORE PRINCIPLE】
------------------------------------------------------------

A civilization is complete only if it possesses four pillars:

Interpretation — defines meaning  
Framework      — forms structure  
Regime         — maintains order  
Operation      — executes action  

If any pillar is missing, the system is incomplete.  
If the pillars are imbalanced, the civilization becomes unstable.

------------------------------------------------------------
【FOUR CANONS (WESTERN EQUIVALENT POSITIONING)】
------------------------------------------------------------

Using canonical Western knowledge systems to map the four pillars:

1. Philosophy / Metaphysics        → Interpretation  
2. Encyclopedic / Scientific Order → Framework  
3. Law / Political Theory         → Regime  
4. Education / Instructional Text → Operation  

------------------------------------------------------------
【PILLAR 1: INTERPRETATION — PHILOSOPHY / METAPHYSICS】
------------------------------------------------------------

Function:
Source of understanding and explanation

Structure:
Being → Substance → Causality → Logic → Possibility → Reality

Examples:
- Greek philosophy (Plato, Aristotle)
- Metaphysics (ontology of being)
- Logic (Aristotelian, later formal logic)

Role:
- defines how the world is understood  
- establishes categories and meaning  
- provides the space of what is possible  

System role:
Civilization’s “Interpretation Engine”

------------------------------------------------------------
【PILLAR 2: FRAMEWORK — SCIENTIFIC & STRUCTURAL KNOWLEDGE】
------------------------------------------------------------

Function:
Map and structure of existence

Structure:
Classification → Measurement → Systematisation → Model-building

Examples:
- Natural sciences (physics, biology, chemistry)
- Taxonomy (classification systems)
- Enlightenment encyclopedias
- Systems thinking and engineering

Role:
- describes the world in structured form  
- organises knowledge into repeatable systems  
- provides a complete map of existence  

System role:
Civilization’s “Structural Framework”

------------------------------------------------------------
【PILLAR 3: REGIME — LAW & GOVERNANCE】
------------------------------------------------------------

Function:
Constraint, legitimacy, and order

Structure:
Law → Rights → Authority → Enforcement → Legitimacy

Examples:
- Roman law
- Constitutional systems
- Political philosophy (Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau)
- Modern governance and institutions

Role:
- defines boundaries and permissible action  
- assigns authority and responsibility  
- stabilises coordination across society  

System role:
Civilization’s “Governance and Constraint System”

------------------------------------------------------------
【PILLAR 4: OPERATION — EDUCATION & EXECUTION】
------------------------------------------------------------

Function:
Action, behaviour, and implementation

Structure:
Instruction → Training → Practice → Habit → Execution

Examples:
- Education systems (schools, curriculum)
- Instructional texts (alphabets, primers, manuals)
- Professional training systems
- Applied engineering and operations

Role:
- translates rules into behaviour  
- embeds knowledge into individuals  
- ensures consistent execution  

System role:
Civilization’s “Operational and Behavioural Layer”

------------------------------------------------------------
【FOUR-PILLAR INTERACTION MECHANISM】
------------------------------------------------------------

Interpretation → Framework
- meaning defines structure

Framework → Regime
- structure informs rules

Regime → Operation
- rules constrain action

Operation → Outcome → Feedback → Interpretation
- results refine understanding

Full loop:

Understanding → Structure → Constraint → Action → Feedback → Renewal

------------------------------------------------------------
【DYNAMIC LOOP】
------------------------------------------------------------

Interpretation → Decision → Action → Result → Knowledge → Regulation → Repeat

Equivalent:

Meaning → Structure → Order → Execution → Feedback → Continuation

------------------------------------------------------------
【SYSTEM PROPERTIES】
------------------------------------------------------------

1. Completeness:
- covers interpretation, structure, constraint, execution

2. Interpretability:
- actions can be explained through reason and knowledge

3. Adaptability:
- institutions evolve through feedback

4. Continuation:
- sustained through education and recorded knowledge

5. Non-determinism:
- uncertainty handled via science and probabilistic reasoning

------------------------------------------------------------
【FAILURE MODES】
------------------------------------------------------------

Interpretation failure:
- incorrect worldview → wrong models

Framework failure:
- incorrect structure → system misrepresentation

Regime failure:
- broken institutions → disorder or instability

Operation failure:
- inability to execute → collapse of system function

------------------------------------------------------------
【FOUR-LEVEL CORRESPONDENCE】
------------------------------------------------------------

Interpretation Layer:
- Philosophy / Metaphysics

Structural Layer:
- Science / Knowledge Systems

Governance Layer:
- Law / Institutions

Execution Layer:
- Education / Practice

------------------------------------------------------------
【ONE-LINE SUMMARY】
------------------------------------------------------------

Through philosophy it defines meaning, through science it structures the world, through law it maintains order, and through education it executes action — this is the Western operational expression of the same civilizational system.
